content.title: Foreword
content.description:
This Technical Specification has been produced by the 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP).
The contents of the present document are subject to continuing work within the TSG and may change following formal TSG approval. Should the TSG modify the contents of the present document, it will be re-released by the TSG with an identifying change of release date and an increase in version number as follows:
Version x.y.z
where:
x	the first digit:
1	presented to TSG for information;
2	presented to TSG for approval;
3	or greater indicates TSG approved document under change control.
y	the second digit is incremented for all changes of substance, i.e. technical enhancements, corrections, updates, etc.
z	the third digit is incremented when editorial only changes have been incorporated in the document.

subsections.title: 3.4	Management Object design and representation guidelines
4.1	General
subsections.text_content:
The MCPTT UE configuration Management Object (MO) is used to configure MCPTT Client behaviour for the on-network or off-network MCPTT Service. The MCPTT UE configuration parameters may be stored in the ME, or in the USIM as specified in 3GPP TS 31.102 [10], or in both the ME and the USIM. If both the ME and the USIM contain the same parameters, the values stored in the USIM shall take precedence.
The Management Object Identifier is: urn:oma:mo:ext-3gpp-MCPTT-UE-configuration:1.0.
Protocol compatibility: This MO is compatible with OMA OMA DM 1.2 [3].
The OMA DM ACL property mechanism (see OMA OMA-ERELD-DM-V1_2 [2]) may be used to grant or deny access rights to OMA DM servers in order to modify nodes and leaf objects of the MCPTT UE configuration MO.
The following nodes and leaf objects are possible under the MCPTT UE configuration node as described in figure 4.1.1.
Figure 4.1.1 presents the configuration of a Mission-Critical Push-to-Talk (MCPTT) User Equipment (UE), which is a crucial component in modern telecommunication systems. The figure illustrates the UE's setup, including the various interfaces and protocols it utilizes for communication. The diagram highlights the importance of secure and efficient data transmission in critical situations, emphasizing the role of the UE in ensuring reliable and rapid communication. The figure also underscores the complexity of modern telecommunication systems, with multiple layers of technology working together to provide seamless communication services.
Figure 4.1.1: The MCPTT UE configuration MO

subsections.title: 5.1	General
subsections.text_content:
The MCPTT user profile configuration Management Object (MO) is used to configure the MCPTT Client behaviour for the on-network or off-network MCPTT Service. The MCPTT user profile configuration parameters may be stored in the ME, or in the USIM as specified in 3GPP TS 31.102 [10], or in both the ME and the USIM. If both the ME and the USIM contain the same parameters, the values stored in the USIM shall take precedence.
The Management Object Identifier is: urn:oma:mo:ext-3gpp-MCPTT-user-profile:1.0.
Protocol compatibility: This MO is compatible with OMA OMA DM 1.2 [3].
The OMA DM ACL property mechanism (see OMA OMA-ERELD-DM-V1_2 [2]) may be used to grant or deny access rights to OMA DM servers in order to modify nodes and leaf objects of the MCPTT user profile MO.

subsubsections.title: 5.2.7C	/<x>/<x>/Common/PreSelectedIndication
subsubsections.text_content:
Table 5.2.7C.1: /<x>/<x>/Common/PreSelectedIndication

-	Values: null
When this leaf node is present, this MCPTT user profile MO is designated as the pre-selected MCPTT user profile.
When this leaf node is absent, this MCPTT user profile MO is not designated as the pre-selected MCPTT user profile.
If more than one MCPTT user profile MO is specified for the MCPTT user, then only one MCPTT user profile MO for the MCPTT user shall contain the <x>/Common/PreSelectedIndication leaf node.
If there is only one MCPTT user profile MO specified for the MCPTT user, then it is optional to include the <x>/Common/PreSelectedIndication leaf node.

subsubsections.title: 5.2.9	/<x>/<x>/Common/AuthorisedAlias
subsubsections.text_content:
Table 5.2.9.1: /<x>/<x>/Common/AuthorisedAlias

When set to "true" the MCPTT user is authorised to create and delete aliases of other MCPTT users and their associated MCPTT user profiles.
When set to "false" the MCPTT user is not authorised to create and delete aliases of other MCPTT user and their associated MCPTT user profiles. This is the default if this leaf node is not present.

subsubsections.title: 5.2.10	/<x>/<x>/Common/ParticipantType
subsubsections.text_content:
Table 5.2.10.1: /<x>/<x>/Common/ParticipantType

subsubsections.title:

MCPTTPrivateRecipient/Entry/UserInfoID
subsubsections.text_content:
Table 5.2.29D.1: /<x>/<x>/Common/PrivateCall/EmergencyCall/MCPTTPrivateRecipient/Entry/
UserInfoID

subsubsections.title:
5.2.29F	/<x>/<x>/Common/PrivateCall/EmergencyCall/
MCPTTPrivateRecipient/Entry/Usage
subsubsections.text_content:
Table 5.2.29F.1: /<x>/<x>/Common/PrivateCall/EmergencyCall/MCPTTPrivateRecipient/Entry/Usage

The valid values are 'LocallyDetermined' and 'UsePreConfigured'.
When set to 'LocallyDetermined' then if the MCPTT user selects an MCPTT ID then use that MCPTT ID for the MCPTT emergency private call, if the MCPTT user does not select a MCPTT ID then use the MCPTT ID identified by the MCPTT private recipient ID in clause 5.2.29B for an on-network MCPTT emergency private call.
When set to 'UsePreConfigured' then use the MCPTT ID identified by the MCPTT private recipient ID in clause 5.2.29B for an on-network MCPTT emergency private call.
When set to 'LocallyDetermined' then if the MCPTT user selects an MCPTT user then use the UserInfoID that corresponds to that MCPTT user for the MCPTT emergency private call, if the MCPTT user does not select a MCPTT user then use the User Info ID identified by the UserInfoID in clause 5.2.29D for an off-network MCPTT emergency private call.
When set to 'UsePreConfigured' then use the User Info ID identified by the UserInfoID in clause 5.2.29D for an off-network MCPTT emergency private call.

When set to "false" the MCPTT user is not authorised to make an MCPTT emergency group call functionality enabled.

subsubsections.title:

MCPTTGroupInitiation/Entry/Usage
subsubsections.text_content:
Table 5.2.34D.1: /<x>/<x>/Common/MCPTTGroupCall/EmergencyCall/MCPTTGroupInitiation/Entry/
Usage

The valid values are 'UseCurrentlySelectedGroup' and 'DedicatedGroup'.
When set to 'UseCurrentlySelectedGroup' then if the MCPTT user has currently selected an MCPTT group then use that MCPTT group for an on-network MCPTT emergency group call, if the MCPTT user does not have a currently selected MCPTT group then use the MCPTT group identified by the GroupID in clause 5.2.34B for an MCPTT emergency group call.
When set to 'DedicatedGroup' then use the MCPTT group identified by the GroupID in clause 5.2.34B for an MCPTT emergency group call.

subsections.title: 6.1	General
subsections.text_content:
The MCS group configuration Management Object (MO) is used to configure the MCS Client behaviour for the on-network or off-network MC services. The MCS group configuration parameters may be stored in the ME, or in the USIM as specified in 3GPP TS 31.102 [10], or in both the ME and the USIM. If both the ME and the USIM contain the same parameters, the values stored in the USIM shall take precedence.
NOTE:	For historical reasons some of the elements in the MCS group configuration Management Object (MO) use the terminology "MCPTT", however this MO is common to all MCS with some MCPTT specific elements, some MCData specific elements and some MCVideo specific elements. Not all elements that contain the terminology "MCPTT" are just MCPTT specific. In the clauses that follow, it is made clear what aspects are specific to MCPTT and what aspects are specific to all MC services. MCData specific elements are contained under "MCData" nodes. MCVideo specific elements are contained under "MCVideo" nodes.
The Management Object Identifier is: urn:oma:mo:ext-3gpp-MCPTT-group-configuration:1.0.
Protocol compatibility: This MO is compatible with OMA OMA DM 1.2 [3].
The OMA DM ACL property mechanism (see OMA OMA-ERELD-DM-V1_2 [2]) may be used to grant or deny access rights to OMA DM servers in order to modify nodes and leaf objects of the MCS group configuration MO.
The following nodes and leaf objects are possible under the MCS group configuration node as described in figure 6.1.1.
Figure 6.1.1: The MC S group configuration MO (1 of 5) illustrates a multi-channel signal system with multiple group configurations. The figure shows the arrangement of multiple input, multiple output (MIMO) antennas and the associated signal processing units. The MC S group configuration MO (1 of 5) highlights the optimization of signal processing and transmission efficiency, enabling higher data rates and improved coverage in wireless communication systems.
Figure 6.1.1: The MCS group configuration MO (1 of 5)
Figure 6.1.2 presents a detailed configuration of the MCS group, illustrating the various parameters that define the modulation, coding, and signaling parameters for a specific communication channel. The figure showcases multiple MCS groups, each with distinct parameters such as the number of subcarriers, spreading factors, and coding rates. These configurations are crucial for optimizing the performance of a wireless communication system, as they determine the efficiency and reliability of data transmission. The figure also highlights the importance of fine-tuning these parameters to achieve the best possible balance between throughput, latency, and energy consumption.
Figure 6.1.2: The MCS group configuration MO (2 of 5)
Figure 6.1.3 illustrates the MCS group configuration MO (3 of 5), showcasing the modulation and coding scheme (MCS) levels for a specific channel bandwidth. The figure displays a range of MCS options, from low to high, with corresponding data rates and signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) thresholds. The visual representation helps in understanding the trade-offs between data rate and energy consumption, enabling network operators to optimize their networks for maximum efficiency and performance.
Figure 6.1.3: The MCS group configuration MO (3 of 5)
Figure 6.1.4 presents a detailed configuration of a Multi-Carrier System (MCS) group, specifically focusing on the MO (Modulation and Coding Scheme) for a 4G network. The figure illustrates the various parameters that define the MCS group, such as the number of Resource Blocks (RBs), the RB size, the CP (Carrier Phase), and the Modulation and Coding Scheme. These parameters are crucial for optimizing the network's performance and ensuring efficient data transmission. The figure also highlights the importance of selecting the appropriate MCS group for different network conditions, such as varying signal strength and user traffic, to maintain optimal network performance.
Figure 6.1.4: The MCS group configuration MO (4 of 5)
Figure 6.1.5 presents a detailed configuration of the MCS group, specifically focusing on the MO (Modulation and Coding Scheme) for a 5G network. The figure illustrates the various parameters that define the MCS group, such as the number of subcarriers, the number of users per subcarrier, the cyclic prefix length, and the maximum number of supported bit rates. These parameters are crucial for determining the overall performance and capacity of the 5G network, as they influence factors such as spectral efficiency, latency, and reliability. The figure also highlights the importance of optimizing these parameters to achieve the desired balance between performance and resource utilization.
Figure 6.1.5: The MCS group configuration MO (5 of 5)

subsections.title: 7.1	General
subsections.text_content:
The MCPTT service configuration Management Object (MO) is used to configure MCPTT Client behaviour for the on-network or off-network MCPTT Service. The MCPTT service configuration parameters may be stored in the ME, or in the USIM as specified in 3GPP TS 31.102 [10], or in both the ME and the USIM. If both the ME and the USIM contain the same parameters, the values stored in the USIM shall take precedence.
The Management Object Identifier is: urn:oma:mo:ext-3gpp-MCPTT-service-configuration:1.0.
Protocol compatibility: This MO is compatible with OMA OMA DM 1.2 [3].
The OMA DM ACL property mechanism (see OMA OMA-ERELD-DM-V1_2 [2]) may be used to grant or deny access rights to OMA DM servers in order to modify nodes and leaf objects of the MCPTT service configuration MO.
The following nodes and leaf objects are possible under the MCPTT service configuration node as described in figure 7.1.1.
Figure 7.1.1 illustrates the multi-channel push-to-talk (MCPTT) service configuration model, showcasing the various components involved in its operation. The figure depicts the core network elements, such as the mobile switching center (MSC), the home location register (HLR), and the universal public land mobile communication system (UTRAN), which work together to provide secure and efficient communication services. The model also highlights the role of the mobile network operator (MNO) in managing the service configuration and ensuring seamless connectivity for users.
Figure 7.1.1: The MCPTT service configuration MO

subsections.text_content:
The MCS UE initial configuration Management Object (MO) is used to configure the MCS Client behaviour for the on-network or off-network MCS Service. The MCS UE initial configuration parameters may be stored in the ME, or in the USIM as specified in 3GPP TS 31.102 [10], or in both the ME and the USIM. If both the ME and the USIM contain the same parameters, the values stored in the USIM shall take precedence.
NOTE:	For historical reasons some of the elements in the MCS UE initial MO uses the terminology "MCPTT", however this MO is common to all MCS with some MCPTT specific elements, some MCData specific elements and some MCVideo specific elements. Not all elements that contain the terminology "MCPTT" are just MCPTT specific.
The Management Object Identifier is: urn:oma:mo:ext-3gpp-MCPTT-UE-initial-configuration:1.0.
Protocol compatibility: This MO is compatible with OMA OMA DM 1.2 [3].
The OMA DM ACL property mechanism (see OMA OMA-ERELD-DM-V1_2 [2]) may be used to grant or deny access rights to OMA DM servers in order to modify nodes and leaf objects of the MCPTT user profile MO.
The following nodes and leaf objects are possible under the MCPTT node as described in figure 8.1.1, figure 8.1.2, figure 8.1.3 and figure 8.1.4.

The figure is segmented into six parts, each representing a different stage in the UE's configuration process. The visual elements, such as the RAT connections and RRM status, provide insights into the UE's readiness for data transmission and the overall network performance. The figure is crucial for network engineers to understand the UE's initial state and to optimize the network configuration for efficient resource allocation and optimal performance.

The figure depicts the UE's initial state, showing the assigned resource blocks (RB) and the modulation and coding scheme (MCS) parameters. subsections.title: 9.1	General
subsections.text_content:
The MCData UE configuration Management Object (MO) is used to configure MCData Client behaviour for the on-network or off-network MCData Service. The MCData UE configuration parameters may be stored in the ME, or in the USIM as specified in 3GPP TS 31.102 [10], or in both the ME and the USIM. If both the ME and the USIM contain the same parameters, the values stored in the USIM shall take precedence.
The Management Object Identifier is: urn:oma:mo:ext-3gpp-MCData-UE-configuration:1.0.
Protocol compatibility: This MO is compatible with OMA OMA DM 1.2 [3].
The OMA DM ACL property mechanism (see OMA OMA-ERELD-DM-V1_2 [2]) may be used to grant or deny access rights to OMA DM servers in order to modify nodes and leaf objects of the MCData UE configuration MO.
The following nodes and leaf objects are possible under the MCData UE configuration node as described in figure 9.1.1 and figure 9.1.2.
Figure 9.1.1 illustrates the MCData UE configuration MO (1 of 2), showcasing the detailed settings for a user equipment (UE) in a multi-carrier data (MCData) environment. The figure presents a hierarchical view of the UE configuration, with various parameters and options organized in a structured manner. subsections.title: 10.1	General
subsections.text_content:
The MCData user profile configuration Management Object (MO) is used to configure the MCData Client behaviour for the on-network or off-network MCData Service. The MCData user profile configuration parameters may be stored in the ME, or in the USIM as specified in 3GPP TS 31.102 [10], or in both the ME and the USIM. If both the ME and the USIM contain the same parameters, the values stored in the USIM shall take precedence.
The Management Object Identifier is: urn:oma:mo:ext-3gpp-MCData-user-profile:1.0.
Protocol compatibility: This MO is compatible with OMA OMA DM 1.2 [3].
The OMA DM ACL property mechanism (see OMA OMA-ERELD-DM-V1_2 [2]) may be used to grant or deny access rights to OMA DM servers in order to modify nodes and leaf objects of the MCData user profile MO.
The following nodes and leaf objects are possible under the MCData user profile node as described in figures 10.1.1 through 10.1.5.
Figure 10.1.1, titled "The MCData user profile MO (1 of 5)," provides a detailed breakdown of a user profile in a multi-channel data system. The figure illustrates the various components and their interactions within the user profile, including the data channels, the user's data, and the system's response. The diagram emphasizes the importance of accurate and efficient data transmission, as well as the role of the MCData system in managing and organizing the data. The figure also highlights the need for synchronization and coordination among the different channels and components to ensure seamless data processing and delivery.
Figure 10.1.1: The MCData user profile MO (1 of 5)
Figure 10.1.2 illustrates the MCData user profile MO (2 of 5), which provides a detailed breakdown of user data usage across various services. The figure showcases a matrix layout, with rows representing different service categories and columns indicating different user profiles. Each cell in the matrix represents the amount of data consumed by a specific user profile within a particular service category. The visual representation allows for easy comparison and analysis of data consumption patterns across different services and user groups.
Figure 10.1.2: The MCData user profile MO (2 of 5)
Figure 10.1.3 illustrates the MCData user profile MO (3 of 5), which provides a detailed breakdown of user data usage across various services. The figure showcases the distribution of data consumption, with different colors representing distinct service categories. Key components include the user equipment (UE), mobile network operator (MNO), and service providers, emphasizing the complex interplay between them. The visual representation highlights the importance of accurate data management and allocation for optimal network performance and user satisfaction.
Figure 10.1.3: The MCData user profile MO (3 of 5)
Figure 10.1.4 illustrates the MCData user profile MO (4 of 5), which provides a detailed breakdown of user data usage. The figure showcases various categories of data consumption, including voice, SMS, and data services, as well as their respective usage patterns. The visual representation of data usage allows for a clear understanding of how users interact with different services and the overall impact on network resources. The figure emphasizes the importance of accurate data profiling for effective resource allocation and billing in mobile networks.

subsections.title: 11.1	General
subsections.text_content:
The MCData service configuration Management Object (MO) is used to configure MCData Client behaviour for the on-network or off-network MCData Service. The MCData service configuration parameters may be stored in the ME, or in the USIM as specified in 3GPP TS 31.102 [10], or in both the ME and the USIM. If both the ME and the USIM contain the same parameters, the values stored in the USIM shall take precedence.
The Management Object Identifier is: urn:oma:mo:ext-3gpp-MCData-service-configuration:1.0.
Protocol compatibility: This MO is compatible with OMA OMA DM 1.2 [3].
The OMA DM ACL property mechanism (see OMA OMA-ERELD-DM-V1_2 [2]) may be used to grant or deny access rights to OMA DM servers in order to modify nodes and leaf objects of the MCData service configuration MO.
The following nodes and leaf objects are possible under the MCData service configuration node as described in figure 11.1.1.
Figure 11.1.1 presents the detailed configuration of the MCData service, illustrating the various components and their interconnections. The figure showcases the service model, including the service provider, service provider network, and service configuration. Key elements such as the service instance, service instance configuration, and service instance MO are clearly depicted, providing a comprehensive overview of the service's architecture and configuration process.
Figure 11.1.1: The MCData service configuration MO

subsections.title: 14.1	General
subsections.text_content:
The MCVideo service configuration Management Object (MO) is used to configure MCVideo Client behaviour for the on-network or off-network MCVideo Service. The MCVideo service configuration parameters may be stored in the ME, or in the USIM as specified in 3GPP TS 31.102 [10], or in both the ME and the USIM. If both the ME and the USIM contain the same parameters, the values stored in the USIM shall take precedence.
The Management Object Identifier is: urn:oma:mo:ext-3gpp-MCVideo-service-configuration:1.0.
Protocol compatibility: This MO is compatible with OMA OMA DM 1.2 [3].
The OMA DM ACL property mechanism (see OMA OMA-ERELD-DM-V1_2 [2]) may be used to grant or deny access rights to OMA DM servers in order to modify nodes and leaf objects of the MCVideo service configuration MO.
The following nodes and leaf objects are possible under the MCVideo service configuration node as described in figure 14.1.1.
Figure 14.1.1 illustrates the MCVideo service configuration model, showcasing the various components and their interactions. The figure depicts a network setup with multiple nodes, including the MCVideo service node, which is the central hub for video processing and distribution. The model also includes edge nodes, which are responsible for local processing and content caching to reduce latency. The figure emphasizes the importance of efficient resource allocation and network optimization for delivering high-quality video services.

content.title: L.1	General
content.description: The present document applies to both EPS and 5GS. This annex lists the aspects of Mission Critical Services (MCSs) Management Objects (MO) which are different in 5GS from EPS. Certain aspects that are only applicable to EPS are described in clause L.2. 5GS-specific concepts are captured in clause L.3. A mapping of EPS-specific terms to their 5GS equivalents is provided in clause L.4.

content.title: L.2	Aspects not applicable to 5GS
content.description:
The following aspects of EPS mentioned in the present document are not applicable to 5GS:
-	Multimedia Broadcast and Multicast Service (MBMS) and the corresponding MOs.

content.title: L.3	5GS specific aspects not applicable to EPS
content.description: In order to identify a Network Slice end to end, the 5GS uses information called S-NSSAI (Single Network Slice Selection Assistance Information) as specified in 3GPP TS 23.501 [23]. Network slicing and the S-NSSAI related configuration are not applicable to EPS.

content.title: L.4	Mapping of EPS-specific terms to 5GS
